Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Boil your #kettle{} then pour the @boiled water{450%ml} into a #measuring jug{}. Add the @chicken stock paste{20%g} and stir well to combine - this is your chicken stock.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large wide-bottomed ovenproof pan{} on medium-high heat.

> TIP: If you don't have an ovenproof pan, use a normal saucepan and transfer to an ovenproof dish later.

Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{90%g} and onion and fry until the onion starts to soften, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the garlic and fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @risotto rice{175%g} to the pan, stir and cook until the edges of the rice are translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in your chicken stock and bring back up to the boil, then pop a #lid{} on the pan (or cover with #foil{}).

Bake on the middle shelf of your #oven{} until the rice is cooked and the water has been absorbed, ~{20-25%minutes}.

When the risotto has 5 mins of cooking time left, drain the @king prawns{150%g}(peeled and deveined). Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the prawns. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and stir-fry for ~{4-5%minutes}. Once cooked, remove the pan from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

When the risotto has finished cooking, remove it from the #oven{} and stir through the @butter{10%g}, @peas{120%g} and half of the @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated).

Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

> TIP: Add a splash of water to loosen the risotto if needed.

Share the chorizo and pea risotto between your #serving bowls{}.

Top with the pan-fried prawns.

Sprinkle over the remaining hard Italian cheese to finish.

Enjoy!